  "summary": "Chief Constable Bartle (also referred to as Batter or Sheriff Bartle) meets Virginia Rue privately under a pine tree on the lawn before reporting to George Romax at Wivenhoe Abbey. Bartle reveals that Mr. Kidd informed him about the letters and the murder that occurred at Virginia's house. He questions Virginia regarding her history with Kidd, suggesting their first meeting took place at her residence on Pound Street. Bartle also inquires about Kidd's past in Canada and Sudan, noting that Kidd's employment at a travel agency lasted only one month. Virginia finds the Sheriff's sharp intellect terrifying.\n\nFollowing Bartle's departure, Bill Everly approaches Virginia to propose marriage, but she rejects him, citing her status as a widow and her age. Monsieur LeMon, a Frenchman, joins them for a walk. While telling stories, LeMon appears to be scouting the courtyard. He observes a luggage car approaching and hitches a ride to the village. When a suitcase marked \"H.I.\" falls from the car, LeMon quickly returns to retrieve it.\n\nUpon opening the leather box, LeMon finds silk clothing and bottles with gold lids. Hidden within a package of silk lingerie, he discovers a heavy handgun. LeMon hides the weapon in his pocket and instructs Bill to intercept an approaching Lancaster sedan to return the suitcase without mentioning LeMon's involvement. Bill informs the driver, Eisakstein, that the suitcase fell out. Once the car passes, LeMon triumphantly reveals the handgun to Bill. Meanwhile, Sheriff Bartle reports to George Romax.",
